        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-30T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-30T01:00:00-05:00" n="1085" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1085">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">033.1193 Nelson, Donald M./5–3045: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-30T13:00:00+07:00">May 30, 1945—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 30—9:43 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>876. Work of Nelson Mission was discussed at length last night at a meeting
                    attended by Kearney<note n="13" xml:id="d1085fn13">A. T. Kearney, ranking
                        officer of the American Production Mission to China.</note> and Brooks,<note n="14" xml:id="d1085fn14">E. P. Brooks, American Production Mission to
                        China.</note> General Olmsted,<note n="15" xml:id="d1085fn15">Brig. Gen.
                        George H. Olmsted, G–5, Civil Affairs Officer, China Theater.</note>
                    representatives of NEA [<hi rend="italic">FEA</hi>]<note n="16" xml:id="d1085fn16">Foreign Economic Administration (FEA).</note> and of the
                    Embassy including Robertson<note n="17" xml:id="d1085fn17">Walter S. Robertson,
                        Minister Counselor for Economic Affairs in China.</note> just arrived. It
                    was agreed among us that, assuming it may be possible to obtain a more effective
                    degree of cooperation from the Chinese authorities (which will require early
                    discussion with and positive action by the Generalissimo), it will be
                    recommended that the Mission be retained in approximately its present form at
                    least until a port and corridor for the supply of China have been opened.
                    Detailed report by air follows, please inform Locke.<note n="18" xml:id="d1085fn18">E. A. Locke, Jr., Assistant to Donald M. Nelson.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
